{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4bf85ce9-07a6-4f0d-9d84-b9ea45645183","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9, so you have the modern constructor injection available.\n\n**Recommended pattern:**\n\n- **Constructor** — for sync init + `TestContext` injection\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — for async init\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private readonly MyService _service;\n\n    // Sync init: constructor with TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SomeTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- MSTest 3.x supports **constructor injection** for `TestContext` — no need for the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- `[TestInitialize]` can be `async Task`, giving you a clean place for async setup.\n- The constructor runs first (sync), then `[TestInitialize]` runs before each test.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7c937bdd-b993-4b3e-b03a-f6e097bb527d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended modern approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest 3.x, `TestContext` can be injected via constructor (no more need for the static property pattern). Actually, let me be precise. Starting with MSTest 3.x:\n   - `TestContext` can be set via a property `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` (the classic way)\n   - Or injected via constructor parameter\n\n2. **Initialization**: \n   - `[TestInitialize]` for synchronous init (can also be async - `public async Task TestInitialize()`)\n   - `[ClassInitialize]` for class-level init, which also supports async methods\n   - Constructor for simple synchronous setup\n\nIn MSTest 3.x, both `TestContext` injection and async initialization methods are fully supported, so the modern pattern would use constructor injection for `TestContext` and async `[TestInitialize]` methods when needed.\n\nWriting the test class structure...","outputTokens":955,"requestId":"0C01:381B5A:3FF87D:4A4E86:69F00DC3"},"id":"6f7a3ea8-8322-49ee-a304-798ee9a53407","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:31:01.963Z","parentId":"a8815c54-435b-41af-8e6f-f8e3419dd407"}
